Dirk,

having hard-coded path is usually lead to trouble regardless of the OS. Users may have dedicated system with specific compiler/tools in different location. What you need is auto-detection of required components. Since /usr/bin is always in a PATH you don't really need it either. But as I described the different location of gcc/g++ requires appropriate linker and if you enforce in your setup specific linker it leads to the problem. My OS X setup is not unique, many Linux systems may have compiler (or even multiple version of compiler) in different location (I work in High-Energy community and we build our tools ourselves, including compiler and the rest of the OS). What matter is consistency and your setup is not consistent with user environment.

If you don't want to introduce robust configure tool chain you can easily create bash script to test location of required tools. If it is required I can write one.

Regards,
Valentin.

